{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592171"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:11:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:11:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15224"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15224"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0,0.57,0.13,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7915"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65337"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7915"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15224"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50776"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"10773"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21710"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65337"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for advice about colorectal cancer screening. Her brother was recently diagnosed with colorectal cancer at age 35. She understands that certain bowel cancers have hereditary origins and would like to know more. The doctor explains that there are various hereditary colorectal cancer syndromes and there is one that follows an autosomal recessive pattern.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following has this inheritance pattern?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Familial adenomatous polyposis","Juvenile polyposis syndrome","Lynch syndrome","MUTYH-associated polyposis","Peutz-Jeghers syndrome"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding inheritance patterns of hereditary cancer syndromes is crucial for appropriate genetic counselling and risk assessment. \u003Cstrong\u003EMUTYH-associated polyposis\u003C/strong\u003E (MAP) is unique among common hereditary colorectal cancer syndromes as it follows an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern, meaning an individual must inherit two mutated copies of the MUTYH gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFamilial adenomatous polyposis\u003C/strong\u003E (FAP) is an autosomal dominant condition caused by mutations in the APC gene. It is characterised by hundreds to thousands of adenomatous polyps throughout the colorectum, with nearly 100% lifetime risk of colorectal cancer if left untreated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELynch syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as hereditary non-polyposis colorectal cancer (HNPCC), is an autosomal dominant condition caused by mutations in DNA mismatch repair genes. It is characterised by early-onset colorectal cancer and increased risk of other cancers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJuvenile polyposis syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an autosomal dominant condition characterised by multiple juvenile polyps throughout the gastrointestinal tract and an increased risk of colorectal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeutz-Jeghers syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an autosomal dominant condition characterised by hamartomatous polyps throughout the gastrointestinal tract and distinctive mucocutaneous pigmentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMAP typically presents with 10-100 colorectal adenomas, fewer than in classical FAP. The lifetime risk of colorectal cancer in MAP is about 43-100% if left untreated. Regular colonoscopic surveillance is recommended for affected individuals and genetic counselling is important for family members.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["MUTYH-associated polyposis (MAP) is the only common hereditary colorectal cancer syndrome that follows an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern.","MAP typically presents with 10-100 colorectal adenomas and carries an increased lifetime risk of colorectal cancer.","Other hereditary colorectal cancer syndromes (FAP, Lynch) follow autosomal dominant inheritance patterns."],"references":["Meseeha M, Attia M. Colon Polyps. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430761/","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Sandler RS. Epidemiology and risk factors for colorectal cancer. Gastroenterol Clin North Am. 1996 Dec;25(4):717-35. doi: 10.1016/s0889-8553(05)70271-5. PMID: 8960889","Rawla P, Sunkara T, Barsouk A. Epidemiology of colorectal cancer: incidence, mortality, survival, and risk factors. Prz Gastroenterol. 2019;14(2):89-103. doi: 10.5114/pg.2018.81072. Epub 2019 Jan 6. PMID: 31616522; PMCID: PMC6791134","Calvert PM, Frucht H. The genetics of colorectal cancer. Ann Intern Med. 2002 Oct 1;137(7):603-12. doi: 10.7326/0003-4819-137-7-200210010-00012. PMID: 12353948"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50776"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1